<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Henry, Alexander. Travels in the Red River Department (Abridged), 1806. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0024</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p><span class="fw">29</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">N<sup>o</sup> 8</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Monday 21</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">This Village consists of Forty huts.  The inhabitants are different from those we had left.  Yet we could discern a Similiarity in their language.  The <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Souliers</span> have the character of brave &#8212; having sustained a war for three years against their neighbours <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Les Gros Ventres</span> a nation <span class="AddHand-author">of</span> three times their number yet obliged to yield and sue for peace continued in amity ever since.  They are stationary the same as the Mandanes with whom they have always been upon good terms.  We stopped here for some time and met with many civilities for which we made some return.  We then went on through a delightful country containing cultivated fields which employed many women and children to keep in order.  The road was covered with people on horseback passing and repassing &#8212; hundreds of horses were seen in all directions feeding beyond the plantations.  The whole part together had that charming appearance which could not be stiled Savage.  We came next to the little villages of the Willow Indians which is situated at the entrance of the Knife River and about a mile distant from the last<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Here the women &amp; children collected together on our arrival and were apparently amising themselves at our expence that is they were making</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">sport</p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[33]</span></p>

